            <fr:title text="Towards univalent reference types › side effects in programming languages"><fr:link href="jms-00OI.xml" title="Towards univalent reference types" addr="jms-00OI" type="local"><fr:em><fr:link href="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2024-univalent.xml" title="Towards univalent reference types" addr="sterling-gratzer-birkedal-2024-univalent" type="local">Towards <fr:strong>univalent</fr:strong> reference types</fr:link></fr:em></fr:link> › side effects in programming languages</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Slide</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Most practical programming languages have <fr:strong><fr:em>side effects</fr:em></fr:strong>: state, input-output, errors, etc.</fr:p><beamer:pause xmlns:beamer="http://ctan.org/pkg/beamer" /><fr:p><fr:strong><fr:em>Monads</fr:em></fr:strong> capture the structure of side effects (<fr:link href="moggi-1991.xml" title="Notions of computation and monads" addr="moggi-1991" type="local">Moggi</fr:link>, <fr:link href="philipwadler.xml" title="Philip Wadler" addr="philipwadler" type="local">Wadler</fr:link>).</fr:p>
 <jms-indent:block xmlns:jms-indent="jonmsterling:indenting">
  
 <jms-indent:row xmlns:jms-indent="jonmsterling:indenting">
   <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {T}\colon  \mathbf {type}\to \mathbf {type}]]></fr:tex>
  </jms-indent:row>

  
 <jms-indent:row xmlns:jms-indent="jonmsterling:indenting">
   <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {ret}\colon  \mathsf {T}\,{A}\to \mathsf {T}\,{A}]]></fr:tex>
